    <h1>Jewel clinches top award for de&#xAD;sign and qual&#xAD;ity</h1>
    <h2>This year&#x2019;s Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore Good De&#xAD;sign Mark top award win&#xAD;ners go be&#xAD;yond brick and mor&#xAD;tar to of&#xAD;fer a holis&#xAD;tic user ex&#xAD;pe&#xAD;ri&#xAD;ence</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200829/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-29"><time>2020-08-29</time></a>
        - <span>FRONT PAGE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Chan&#xAD;tal Sa&#xAD;jan&#xD;&#xA;Se&#xAD;nior Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent chan&#xAD;tal@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;&#x2022; For the full list of SG Mark 2020 win&#xAD;ners, go to sg&#xAD;mark.org.</span>
    </section>

    <p>Jewel Changi Air­port wanted to be more than just a land­mark that re­flects Sin­ga­pore’s as­pi­ra­tions of be­ing a city in a gar­den.</p>
    <p>The mixed-use devel­op­ment, which opened to the pub­lic in April last year, crafted a to­tal life­style ex­pe­ri­ence – with 280 shop­ping and din­ing op­tions for trav­ellers and res­i­dents to soak in the sights, sounds and smells.</p>
    <p>The restau­rants sit on dif­fer­ent lev­els, with sev­eral at the top of the dome, sur­rounded by trees, mak­ing guests feel like they are din­ing in­side a for­est.</p>
    <p>The de­sign melds the phys­i­cal and ex­pe­ri­en­tial fea­tures so seam­lessly that it clinched Jewel the top plat­inum award at the Sin­ga­pore Good De­sign Mark (SG Mark) awards this year.</p>
    <p>There are al­to­gether six top win­ners: one plat­inum award, two gold awards and three spe­cial men­tion awards. Be­sides the top six, there are also 60 SG Mark win­ners .</p>
    <p>The an­nual awards, launched in 2013 by the De­sign Busi­ness Cham­ber Sin­ga­pore (DBCS) in part­ner­ship with the Ja­pan In­sti­tute of De­sign Pro­mo­tion, set bench­marks for good de­sign and qual­ity.</p>
    <p>The top win­ners were an­nounced yes­ter­day in a vir­tual awards cer­e­mony.</p>
    <p>Ms Jean Hung, chief ex­ec­u­tive of­fi­cer of Jewel Changi Air­port Devel­op­ment, tells The Straits Times: “Right from the be­gin­ning, Jewel was con­cep­tu­alised for Changi Air­port to re­main rel­e­vant to chang­ing cus­tomer ex­pec­ta­tions, the grow­ing re­gion and the chang­ing world.</p>
    <p>“The Jewel ex­pe­ri­ence is de­signed to be multi-sen­sory – from the sooth­ing sounds of the HSBC Rain Vor­tex, the small droplets of mist it emits that cre­ate a tin­gling sen­sa­tion on the skin, to the signature scent that per­fumes the mall.”</p>
    <p>DBCS, which has seen a 26 per cent jump in sub­mis­sions this year, notes that com­pa­nies are piv­ot­ing to more user-fo­cused ex­pe­ri­ences such as “ex­pe­ri­ence de­sign” through apps and phys­i­cal stores, and sustainabi­lity through ju­di­cious use of re­sources.</p>
    <p>OCBC’s Frank Store at the Na­tional Uni­ver­sity of Sin­ga­pore’s Uni­ver­sity Town (U-Town), which won a gold award, is an­other ex­am­ple of this ex­pe­ri­en­tial shift.</p>
    <p>Its first open-con­cept Frank Store, which opened in April last year, is dif­fer­ent from other Frank stores in Or­chard Gate­way, Nanyang Te­cho­log­i­cal Uni­ver­sity and Sin­ga­pore Man­age­ment Uni­ver­sity.</p>
    <p>The Frank Store con­cept de­parts from reg­u­lar OCBC bank branch de­signs as it is tar­geted at trendy mil­len­ni­als, al­low­ing them to take their time to browse the ser­vices in a ca­sual set­ting that repli­cates a re­tail shop­ping ex­pe­ri­ence.</p>
    <p>The Frank Store at NUS U-Town goes even fur­ther in its de­sign, aim­ing to be i n sync with the rhythms of cam­pus life. It is de­signed to al­low stu­dents roundthe-clock ac­cess to the premises – to chill with friends, study, en­joy free Wi-Fi or grab a snack from the cash­less vend­ing ma­chine.</p>
    <p>Mr Bo­jan Ble­cic, head of group cus­tomer ex­pe­ri­ence at OCBC, says: “We ap­plied em­pa­thy i n ad­dress­ing stu­dent needs, un­der­stand­ing that they craved a com­fort­able space to call their own on cam­pus.</p>
    <p>“The Frank Store, with its bor­der­less and non-tra­di­tional branch de­sign that does not utilise shutters or bar­ri­ers af­ter op­er­at­ing hours, makes it at­trac­tive for stu­dents to come into the store to take their time to browse con­tent, play games or catch up with their friends over cof­fee.”</p>
    <p>He adds that an­other el­e­ment of the de­sign is sustainabi­lity through the man­age­ment of am­bi­ent tem­per­a­ture.</p>
    <p>The branch is kept cool all the time through evap­o­ra­tive cool­ing in­stead of en­ergy-guz­zling air-con­di­tion­ing. Home-grown com­pany In­nosparks, which pi­o­neered the evap­o­ra­tive tech­nol­ogy, was tasked to cool hot air by 5 deg C with­out re­sort­ing to tra­di­tional coolants.</p>
    <p>Other top award win­ners in­clude</p>
    <p>Sin­ga­pore Air­lines, which bagged a gold for its app which al­lows users a per­son­alised dig­i­tal travel ex­pe­ri­ence; and Na­tional Parks Board for its Seed Bank, which was given spe­cial men­tion in the sus­tain­able de­sign cat­e­gory for up­hold­ing ar­chi­tec­tural legacy while us­ing tech­nol­ogy to pre­serve and man­age seeds in a colo­nial-era build­ing at 1D Cluny Road.</p>
    <p>The repos­i­tory of pre­cious seeds is a state-of-the-art fa­cil­ity in­side a 100-year-old build­ing de­signed by Sin­ga­pore’s old­est ar­chi­tec­ture firm Swan & Ma­claren in 1928 for the Bri­tish gov­ern­ment.</p>
    <p>DBCS pres­i­dent An­drew Pang notes that de­sign is a key driver for sus­tain­able growth.</p>
    <p>“De­sign­ers are nat­u­ral prob­lem solvers who have much to of­fer in pro­vid­ing in­ge­nious so­lu­tions to prob­lems in the world,” he says.</p>
    <p>“They play a key role in not only help­ing com­mu­ni­ties, so­ci­eties, busi­nesses and gov­ern­ments to sur­vive, but also thrive in the new nor­mal that we are be­ing thrust into.”</p>

